Author-Name: James P. Weston 
Author-Workplace-Name: Jones Graduate School of Management, Rice University 
Title: Competition on the Nasdaq and the Impact of Recent Market Reforms 
Abstract:
 This paper examines the effect of recent market reforms on the competitive
 structure of the Nasdaq. Our results show that changes in inventory and
 information costs cannot explain the post-reform decrease in bid-ask
 spreads. We interpret this as evidence that the reforms have reduced
 Nasdaq dealers' rents. Additionally, we find that the difference between
 NYSE and Nasdaq spreads have been greatly diminished with the new rules.
 Further, the reforms have resulted in an exit, "ceteris paribus", from the
 industry for market making. Overall, our results provide strong evidence
 that the reforms have improved competition on the Nasdaq. Copyright The American Finance Association 2000. 
